div.p: data_walk: Instruction-by-instruction trace through context_switch_asm Blue = Old Process Stack Active Green = New Process Stack Active Red = Identity Swap Point

g.text: CALL ENTRY timer IRQ fires, scheduler calls context_switch_asm
SAVE PHASE push callee-saved registers onto OLD stack
SAVE OLD ESP capture stack snapshot into old_ctxesp
IDENTITY SWAP ESP changes: old process new process
RESTORE PHASE pop from NEW process stack
RET new process resumes at its saved EIP
What happens to the OLD process (Process A)?

div.p: ; C call from context_switch(): ; context_switch_asm(&old->context, &new->context) ; cdecl: args pushed right-to-left before CALL ; CALL itself pushes return EIP onto the stack
nasm push ebx ; callee-saved (cdecl ABI) push esi ; callee-saved push edi ; callee-saved push ebp ; frame pointer pushfd ; EFLAGS CRITICAL: saves IF (interrupt flag)
EFLAGS must be saved/restored correctly. IF (bit 9) = 1 means interrupts enabled. If forgotten: new process runs with IRQs disabled forever system freeze. 0x00000202 = bit9(IF)=1 + bit1(reserved)=1
nasm mov eax, [esp+24] ; EAX = old_ctx* (arg0, now at +24 after 5 pushes) mov [eax + 16], esp ; old_ctx->esp = current ESP
nasm mov eax, [esp+28] ; EAX = new_ctx* (arg1, at +28 after 5 pushes) mov esp, [eax + 16] ; ESP = new_ctx->esp PIVOT POINT

nasm popfd ; Restore new process EFLAGS re-enables IRQs (IF=1) pop ebp ; Restore new process EBP pop edi ; Restore new process EDI pop esi ; Restore new process ESI pop ebx ; Restore new process EBX ret ; POP new process EIP from stack resume at saved suspension point

g.text: NEW PROCESS Kernel Stack before pops

div.p: popfd is the IRQ re-enable point. EFLAGS.IF transitions from 0 (inside interrupt handler) to 1 (new process context) at this instruction. After this, the timer can preempt the new process.
nasm ret ; POP EIP from NEW stack jump to 0xC010A234

The ret pops the EIP that was pushed when Process B last called context_switch_asm. For a brand-new process, this is the fabricated entry address set by process_create: c *--stack = (uint32_t)entry_function; // fabricated EIP
Process B resumes exactly where it was suspended it has no knowledge that any time passed.

Process A's state is completely preserved on its kernel stack. Its cpu_context_t.esp = 0xC0A03F80 points to the saved frame. The next time the scheduler picks Process A: context_switch_asm will load esp = old_ctxesp = 0xC0A03F80, then pop EFLAGS EBP EDI ESI EBX ret. Process A resumes at its Return EIP, believing context_switch_asm just returned. From Process A's perspective: context_switch_asm was called and returned normally (possibly thousands of timer ticks later). Zero observable side effects.

g.text: mov [eax+16],esp SAVE OLD ESP into old_ctx
mov esp,[eax+16] LOAD NEW ESP IDENTITY SWAP
ret POP new EIP resume Process B

div.p: [ESP+28] new_ctx* ptr to new PCB context
[ESP+24] old_ctx* ptr to old PCB context
[ESP+20] Return EIP pushed by CALL instruction

g.text: ESP points here at function entry

div.p: [ESP+20] Return EIP
[ESP+4] EBP = 0xC0A03FE0
[ESP+0] EFLAGS = 0x00000202 IF=1 (bit 9)

g.text: offset 0: edi (not stored lives on stack)
offset 4: esi (not stored lives on stack)
offset 8: ebx (not stored lives on stack)
offset 12: ebp (not stored lives on stack)
offset 20: eip (was Return EIP on stack)
offset 24: eflags (lives on stack as pushfd)

div.p: The struct stores only ESP. All other registers live ON the stack pointed to by that ESP. This is the minimal representation the stack IS the saved context.

ul.li: This single instruction IS the context switch

g.text: offset 16: esp = 0xC0B07F40 READ NOW (loaded into ESP)

div.p: This value was stored when Process B was last switched out. (Or fabricated by process_create for first-time scheduling.)
[ESP+20] Return EIP = 0xC010A234 ret will jump here
[ESP+4] EBP = 0xC0B07FE0
[ESP+0] EFLAGS = 0x00000202 popfd restores IF=1 (IRQs re-enabled)

g.text: ESP = 0xC0B07F58 (Process B's kernel stack, 5 words above saved frame)
CR3 = Phys addr of Process B page dir (set before context_switch_asm)
TSS.ESP0 = Process B kernel_stack_top (set before context_switch_asm)
